# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS J AND WHY IS IT THE 72ND LANGUAGE?
#
# J (https://jsoftware.com, https://github.com/jsoftware/jsource,
# 735+ stars on GitHub mirror) is **Kenneth Iverson and Roger Hui's
# array-oriented programming language** — the direct ASCII-syntax
# successor to APL.  Created in 1990 by Iverson + Hui at JPMorgan
# Chase Asset Management (Hui's then-employer), J was designed to
# make APL's array-programming model usable in modern computing
# environments without requiring special keyboards/fonts/Unicode
# support.
#
# J's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. ASCII-ONLY APL — APL uses special characters (α β γ δ ⌽ ⍒
#      ⊥ ⊤ ⊆ ⊇ ⌹ ⌷ ⊂ ⊃ etc.) that historically required APL
#      keyboards / specialized fonts / character-encoding gymnastics.
#      J reformulates the same array-programming primitives in pure
#      ASCII:
#         APL          J equivalent          Meaning
#         ---          ------------          -------
#         ⍴             #                     Tally / count
#         +/            +/                    Sum
#         ⊢            ]                     Right argument
#         ⊣            [                     Left argument
#         ⌽            |.                    Reverse
#         ∊            e.                    Member of
#         ↑            {.                     First / head
#         ↓             }.                    Drop / tail
#         ⍳            i.                    Index generator
#         ⊃            >                     Open boxed values
#         ⊂            <                     Box (enclose)
#         ÷            %                     Divide
#         ⌈            >.                    Maximum / ceiling
#         ⌊            <.                    Minimum / floor
#         ○            o.                    Pi-times / trig
#      Compare every other documented language — none preserve APL's
#      single-character verb-naming convention while using ASCII.
#      FIRST documented ASCII-only direct-APL-descendant language.
#
#   2. VERBS / ADVERBS / CONJUNCTIONS PARTS OF SPEECH — J's language
#      has a LINGUISTIC structure inherited from APL:
#         - Nouns: data (arrays, numbers, strings)
#         - Verbs: functions on data (`+`, `-`, `*`, `%`, `#`, `i.`)
#         - Adverbs: modifiers of verbs (`/` reduce, `\` scan, `~`
#           reflexive, `:` define)
#         - Conjunctions: binary modifiers of verb pairs (`&` bind,
#           `@` compose, `&.` under, `:` rank)
#         - Copula: assignment (`=:` global, `=.` local)
#         - Punctuation: control flow (`if. else. end.`)
#      This LINGUISTIC vocabulary lets J programmers think of code
#      as English-like sentences.  Compare every other documented
#      language — none have explicit verb/adverb/conjunction parts-
#      of-speech as language-level primitives.  FIRST documented
#      language with linguistic-categorized syntactic primitives.
#
#   3. TACIT PROGRAMMING (POINT-FREE FORM) — J encourages programs
#      written WITHOUT NAMED ARGUMENTS by composing verbs:
#
#          NB. Mean of an array
#          NB. Explicit form (with named argument)
#          mean =: 4 : '(+/y) % # y'
#          mean 1 2 3 4 5   NB. yields 3
#
#          NB. Tacit form (no named arguments — VERB TRAIN)
#          mean =: +/ % #
#          mean 1 2 3 4 5   NB. yields 3
#
#      The 3-verb train `+/ % #` reads as "sum divided by count" —
#      J's interpreter recognizes the (verb verb verb) pattern as a
#      FORK and applies it as `(+/ x) % (# x)`.  Compare:
#         * Haskell's point-free style: `f . g . h` composition
#         * Combinatory logic (SKI): pure combinators
#         * Concatenative langs (Factor, Joy): stack-based no args
#         * J: PARTS-OF-SPEECH-AWARE tacit programming with verb
#              trains (fork/hook patterns)
#      FIRST documented language with PART-OF-SPEECH-AWARE TACIT
#      programming via verb trains.
#
#   4. RIGHT-TO-LEFT EVALUATION — J evaluates expressions right-to-
#      left without operator precedence:
#         3 + 4 * 5         NB. J yields 23 (= 3 + (4*5)) NOT 35
#         3 * 4 + 5         NB. J yields 27 (= 3 * (4+5)) NOT 17
#         a + b - c + d     NB. J yields a + (b - (c + d))
#      All verbs have the SAME precedence — evaluation is purely
#      right-associative.  This is INHERITED from APL.  Compare
#      every other documented language — all use standard
#      mathematical operator precedence (PEMDAS or similar).
#      FIRST documented language with uniform right-to-left verb
#      evaluation (no operator precedence).
#
#   5. BOX TYPE FOR NESTED ARRAYS — J's `<` (box) verb wraps
#      heterogeneous data into a "box" that becomes a scalar in an
#      enclosing array.  This is J's mechanism for nested
#      structures since J arrays are rectangular:
#
#          5 < 5            NB. 1 (5 less than 5 is false→0 actually wait
#                            NB. monadic < boxes; dyadic is less-than)
#          < 'hello'        NB. boxes the string into a scalar
#          (<'a';3);('b';5)
#                            NB. nested boxed structure
#          >: < 1 2 3        NB. unbox + increment: 2 3 4
#
#      The box mechanism is APL/J's equivalent of struct/record
#      types in conventional languages — but it's a VALUE, not a
#      type-system feature.  FIRST documented language where
#      "structured data" is a runtime value-wrapping operation
#      rather than a type-system construct.
#
#   6. JPMORGAN-CHASE-FINANCIAL-INDUSTRY PROVENANCE — J was
#      created at JPMorgan Chase Asset Management where Roger Hui
#      worked.  J's design was influenced by quant-finance
#      requirements: dealing with large historical price arrays,
#      time-series operations (windowed reductions, lagged
#      differences), and statistical computations.  J's array
#      primitives map directly to financial analytics:
#         +/\ prices       NB. Cumulative sum
#         2 -/\ prices     NB. Pairwise differences (price deltas)
#         (10 # 0.1)+/. prices  NB. 10-period moving average
#         %/ prices        NB. Geometric mean
#      Compare:
#         * Yorick R553:    LLNL national-lab provenance (nuclear
#                            weapons research)
#         * Modelica R529:  Linköping University academic
#                            provenance
#         * COBOL R541:     CODASYL business consortium
#         * J:               JPMorgan Chase financial-services
#                            provenance
#      FIRST documented FINANCIAL-INDUSTRY-PROVENANCE language.
#
# J's relationship to other documented languages:
#
#   * Like APL (1962)   — direct ASCII descendant; same array-
#                          programming model
#   * Like Yorick R553   — array-oriented numerical computing
#   * Like Wolfram R549   — terse mathematical notation
#   * Like Haskell        — supports point-free (tacit) style
#   * Like Factor / Joy  — concatenative/tacit composition
#   * Like K/Q (kdb+)    — array language (Arthur Whitney's K/Q
#                            shares APL ancestry — Whitney worked
#                            with Iverson)
#   * Unlike all of the above — UNIFORM RIGHT-TO-LEFT EVALUATION +
#                                PARTS-OF-SPEECH (verbs/adverbs/
#                                conjunctions) + VERB TRAINS +
#                                BOX TYPE for nesting.  J is
#                                uniquely positioned in the
#                                array-language space as the
#                                ASCII-direct-APL-successor with
#                                linguistic syntactic primitives.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE jconsole CLI — Hand-Rolled C strcmp + Argv-Removal Trick
#
# jconsole's argv parser is a hand-rolled C strcmp-based loop in
# jsrc/jconsole.c that DOES POSITION-INDEPENDENT flag detection
# (unlike Yorick R553's position-dependent first-arg-only check):
#
#     int i,poslib=0,poslibpath=0,posnorl=0,posnoel=0,
#         posprmpt=0,posscrpt=0,posjversion=0;
#     for(i=1;i<argc;i++){
#         if(!poslib&&!strcmp(argv[i],"-lib")){
#             poslib=i;
#             if((i<argc-1)&&('-'!=*(argv[i+1])))poslibpath=i+1;
#         }
#         else if(!posnorl&&!strcmp(argv[i],"-version"))
#             {posjversion=i; jversion=1;}
#         else if(!posnorl&&!strcmp(argv[i],"-norl"))
#             {posnorl=i; norl=1;}
#         else if(!posnoel&&!strcmp(argv[i],"-noel"))
#             {posnoel=i; noel=1;}
#         else if(!posprmpt&&!strcmp(argv[i],"-prompt"))
#             {posprmpt=i; forceprmpt=1;}
#         else if(!posscrpt&&!strcmp(argv[i],"-jscript"))
#             {posscrpt=i; runjscript=1; norl=1; noel=1;
#              forceprmpt=0;}
#     }
#     /* remove processed args */
#     if(poslib||poslibpath||posnorl||posnoel||posprmpt||posscrpt
#        ||posjversion){
#         int j=0;
#         char **argvv = malloc(argc*sizeof(char*));
#         argvv[j++]=argv[0];
#         for(i=1;i<argc;i++){
#             if(!(i==poslib||i==poslibpath||i==posnorl||i==posnoel
#                  ||i==posprmpt||i==posscrpt||i==posjversion))
#                 argvv[j++]=argv[i];
#         }
#         argc=j;
#         for(i=1;i<argc;++i)argv[i]=argvv[i];
#         free(argvv);
#     }
#
# The ARGV-REMOVAL TRICK is the distinguishing feature: after
# identifying recognized flags by position, jconsole allocates a
# new argv array containing ONLY the unrecognized args, copies it
# back over the original argv, and reduces argc.  This lets the J
# interpreter see ONLY user-script args (not the engine's own
# flags) when populating the J `ARGV_z_` global.
#
# Distinct from Yorick R553 (the only other documented hand-rolled
# strcmp argv parser) on FIVE specific axes:
#
#   1. POSITION-INDEPENDENT FLAG DETECTION — Yorick R553's argv
#      parser checks `argv[1]` specifically for `-batch` (position-
#      dependent first-arg-only).  jconsole's argv parser loops
#      through ALL argv positions checking each for any of the
#      seven recognized flags (position-independent).  FIRST
#      documented C strcmp argv parser with position-independent
#      flag detection.
#
#   2. ARGV-REMOVAL POST-PROCESSING — Yorick R553's parser doesn't
#      modify argv after processing.  jconsole's parser MUTATES
#      argv after processing — recognized flags are removed and
#      argc is reduced so the J interpreter sees only user args.
#      FIRST documented CLI library with argv-removal post-
#      processing trick.
#
#   3. FLAG-COMBINATION SIDE EFFECTS — jconsole's `-jscript` flag
#      automatically sets `norl=1` (no readline), `noel=1` (no
#      editline), and `forceprmpt=0` (no prompt) — encoding the
#      "running as a script" intent into multiple internal flags.
#      Compare every other documented CLI library — most expose
#      each flag independently.  FIRST documented CLI library with
#      single-flag-sets-multiple-internal-flags semantics.
#
#   4. SINGLE-DASH LONG OPTION (J/APL CONVENTION) — jconsole uses
#      `-version`, `-norl`, `-noel`, `-prompt`, `-jscript`, `-lib`
#      (single-dash long-form).  Like Yorick R553 (LLNL Fortran
#      tradition) and Wolfram Language R549 (Mathematica
#      tradition), jconsole inherits a pre-GNU-double-dash
#      convention — but specifically from APL/J 1990s convention
#      (APL CLIs always used single-dash).  FIRST documented APL/
#      J-tradition single-dash CLI convention.
#
#   5. NO -h / --help HANDLER — Like Yorick R553, jconsole has
#      literally no `-h` or `--help` flag.  Users learn the CLI
#      from the jsoftware.com documentation, the `jconsole`
#      manpage, or the J community wiki.  SECOND documented CLI
#      library with literally no --help mechanism (alongside
#      Yorick R553).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/jsoftware/jsource/blob/master/jsrc/jconsole.c
# argv parsing loop.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

_arguments -s -S \
    '-lib[load J library from custom directory path]:directory:_directories' \
    '-version[print J version and exit]' \
    '-norl[disable readline (do not use libedit/readline for input)]' \
    '-noel[disable editline (readline) but keep linenoise input]' \
    '-prompt[emit prompt even when stdin is not a terminal (force interactive prompt)]' \
    '-jscript[run J source file as script then exit (no REPL, no readline, no prompt)]' \
    '*:J source file or script argument:_files -g "*.(ijs|ijp)"' \
    && ret=0

return ret
